data.content:
Your test works but has weak assertions — `Assert.IsTrue` gives unhelpful failure messages like "Expected: True, Actual: False". MSTest has dedicated collection assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // All users should be active
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Verify admin is present
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)`** — on failure shows `Expected: 3, Actual: 1` instead of just `True/False`
- **`CollectionAssert`** — built-in class with `Contains`, `AllItemsAreNotNull`, `AllItemsAreUnique`, `AreEqual` (order-sensitive), `AreEquivalent` (order-insensitive), `IsSubsetOf`, etc.
- **Message parameters** — add context to `Assert.IsTrue` when you must use it

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**

```csharp
// Exact match (order matters)
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);

// Same items, any order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);

// Check a specific item exists
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);

// All items are a specific type
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(users, typeof(User));
```

**Rule of thumb:** prefer `Assert.AreEqual` / `CollectionAssert` over `Assert.IsTrue` — you get meaningful failure messages for free.
